		OPUSSUM library

1) directory structure
2) install
3) applications


1) directory structure:
builder:	test application to build preprocessed terrain and building datasets
                The test application uses qt for reading images (textures and 
                heightfield) and libshp for reading building outlines. The
                test application is here for demonstrating library features and
                should be adapted and/or rewritten to handle large scale
                datasets

viewer:		test application to visualize preprocessed terrain and building
                datasets. 

lib:		all library files developed for the project and required to
                link the applications.
extra_lib:	external libs required to compile test applications. At this
                point we only added libshp to read shapefiles in the builder

opossum:	interface to access opossum library objects

paris_img:	2 test images: one Paris heightfield and one Paris texture.
		   - ps_paris_9k_uint8.png a one byte version of the paris heightfield.
		   - paris_texture_1k.png a simplified version of the 36000x36000 paris texture.

2) install: (qt is required!)

% cd builder
% qmake builder.pro
% nmake
% cd ../viewer
% qmake viewer.pro
% nmake

3) applications:

3.1) builder: build a texture tree starting from an image.
  usage: opossum_builder [-height height-file-name] 
                         [-color color-file-name] 
                         [-buildings buildings-file-name] 
                         [-output output-file-name]
 Paris Example:
    opossum_builder -height paris_9k_uint8.png -color paris_texture_1k.png -buildings Paris_build3D_all_PolygonZ.shp -output Paris

3.2) opossum_viewer -height height-file-name [-color color-file-name] [-buildings buildings-file-name]

  Paris Example:
    opossum_viewer -height Paris.height [-color Paris.color] [-buildings Paris.buildings]
 
Enjoy.

